fields.task_description: To fulfill the purpose of promoting conservation and enchancement in the Nanaimo River area, the NRSS undertakes and supports public education and outreach activities. The activities range from volunteer participation in salmon enhancement activities and educational viewing opportunities, to school programs and salmon fry release opportunities for the public and students. Most stewardship activities align with the timing of salmon enhancement activities across the year.
fields.activity_title: Public Stewardship

fields.task_description: TCH supports conservation and rebuilding, and harvest enhancement objectives in the Ucluelet area watersheds, Toquaht watershed and enhancement activities in the Clayoquot Sound watersheds that include Tranquil and Upper Kennedy River watersheds. Year round tasks involve implementing best management practices of salmon culture techniques including Salmonid broodstock capture, holding, handling, sorting, spawning, incubation - (inventory, fungus treatments - salt, parasite S, shocking, picking (hand, machine), ponding, marking, flows, experiments, marking (otolith, clips, tags, other), rearing in raceways, channels, tubs, netpens/seapens (diet/growth, pond maintenance, water quality, flow), fish health management, treatment, biosecurity (internal, external), transport, release, adult and juvenile enumeration and sampling. Program preparation, monitoring, troubleshooting, maintenance and clean-up are ongoing tasks. Program strategic planning and broader facilities maintenance occur during periods of reduced biological activity.

fields.expected_results: Not applicable

fields.task_description: Thornton Creek Hatchery works collaboratively with First Nations, volunteer community groups, municipal and federal governments, industry, educational institutions, and other stakeholder groups. The hatchery supports Community Involvement Program Stream to Sea Education programming, including Salmonids in the Classroom. Most stewardship activities align with the timing of salmon enhancement activities throughout the year.
fields.activity_title: Public Stewardship

fields.task_description: The Organization will work with DFO Stock Assessment to plan and implement an adult chum tagging program in the Lower Harrison River Watershed.
fields.activity_title: Lower Harrison River Watershed Adult Chum Tagging
fields.expected_results: 1. Nuxalk Stewardship staff to collect and store data and samples from Bella Coola caught salmon from the FSC fishery in 2020 according to agreed upon instructions. 2. Samplers and monitors to be trained in the importance of their work and they will communicate the importance of annual programs for Atnarko Sockeye recovery to the best of their abilities when interacting with fishers and fish processors. 3. All adipose clipped chinook heads will be frozen as instructions provided. Then inventoried and shipped out for dissection by coordinating with Bella Coola DFO Stock Assessment.
fields.dfo_report: 1. All full, partial and emty scale books will be provided from the 2020 season by the end of August separated by species. 2. A complete database with all datasheets transcribed in Excel for sockeye biological sampling, and river-monitoring sheets by October 5th. 3. Hardcopies of all original datasheets from the biological sampling and catch monitoring in order of date for DFO stock assessement to use for troubleshooting any database issues.

fields.task_description: The Organization will work with DFO LFA Resource Management (Catch Monitoring Biologist) to plan and implement a program to monitor the HFA FSC fisheries.  Monitoring of salmon fisheries within the Fraser River will be coordinated with the Fraser Valley Aboriginal Fisheries Society (FVAFS) or other lead organization.
fields.element_title: Food, Social and Ceremonial (FSC) Fisheries Management
fields.activity_title: Food, Social and Ceremonical Management
fields.expected_results: 1.The Fishery Manager will work with LFA Resource Management (Catch Monitoring Biologist) to develop and implement a fishing plan and operational procedures for each fiscal year, and will be reported against in the Year End Reports, through the use of the "FSC Monitoring Tasks Checklist" developed in 2017. 2.Fisheries will be monitored by up to 2 staff (hired or contracted) as required by the target species; staff will support field operations and office activities.
fields.dfo_report: 1.A completed 'FSC Monitoring Tasks Checklist' will be provided in the Year End Reports. 2.The Organization will provide details of the number of individuals hired and community affiliation in the Year End Reports. 3.The Organization will provide details of the type of training and number of staff attended in their Year End Reports.

It is also expected that the coordination of activities between Sts'ailes and DFO FIA Salmon StA to meet the Task Objectives will require meaningful effort on the part of the biological contractor hired by Sts'ailes. 3.All data collected while assisting the delivery of Activities 2 and 3 will be included with the data already being collected in the conduct of Activities 2 and 3 under Sts'ailes' Activities Funding Agreement (AFS2018-MLT-1837-2) and used in the analysis. The data and analysis results will be described in the 2020-21 final technical report that is defined in Sts'ailes' Activities Funding Agreement (AFS2018-MLT-1837-2). 4.All data collected while collaborating with the DFO FIA Salmon StA to estimate Fraser Chum Survey Life will be provided to DFO FIA Salmon StA for inclusion in the final technical report describing all field and analytic methods and results. DFO FIA Salmon StA is responsible for writing and publishing this report. A copy of this report will be provided to Sts'ailes by July 1, 2021.
fields.dfo_report: 1.PST funding will be used to increase data collection of Key Element A/Activity 2 - Lower Harrison River Watershed Adult Chum Tagging to improve accuracy and precision of the current statement of work developed in cooperation with DFO FIA Salmon StA. 2.PST funding will be used to improve delivery of Key Element A/Activity 3 - Stream Surveys in a manner consistent with the current statement of work developed in cooperation with DFO FIA Salmon StA. 3.All data collected while assisting with the delivery of Activities 2 and 3 above will be included with the data already being collected under the current statement of work and used in the analysis. The data and analysis results will be described in the 2020-21 final technical report.

fields.task_description: The Organization works with DFO to conduct adult salmon enumeration and biological sampling at the Stamp, Sproat River and Great Central Lake fish ways from May until November. Work is done under contract with DFO South Coast Stock Assessment Unit (Diana Dobson). The Organization's AFS funded guardian (non-designated) and fisheries manager assist other Hupacasath staff with this work as well as interact with DFO assessment staff regularly throughout the duration of the program. 2.
fields.activity_title: Fall Salmon (non-Sockeye) Stock Assessment
fields.expected_results: Spawning escapement areas adjacent to communities are closely monitored. Spawning escapement data is systematically collected, stored and/or disseminated to DFO and others. Field related equipment is acquired, issued and maintained. Individuals are deployed to targeted areas to conduct field work in support of spawning escapement monitoring activities. The Organization's members gain technical expertise. Individuals (at least two) are employed or contracted by the Organization in support of monitoring of spawning escapement.
fields.dfo_report: All datasheets, including Daily Activity Sheets, bypass count sheets and biological data sheets will be faxed to DFO StAD staff or entered into the VidEsc database according to the schedule below for the duration of the contract.  Provide to DFO StAD staff the Daily Activity Sheet by the end of each day the site(s) were visited.Provide to DFO StAD staff updated escapement counts through input into the VidEsc database on a daily basis.Provide to DFO StAD staff the Bypass and the Biological Sample data by the end of the day on which the sampling/monitoring has taken place. This information will be entered into the VidEsc database.   Provide the completed scale books to DFO StAD staff by each Tuesday 10:00 AM until the counting apparatus is removed in approximately mid-November (courier to Carmen McConnell at DFO, South Coast/STAD, 3225 Stephenson Point Road, Nanaimo, B.C. V9T 1K3, unless other arrangements are made for sample pick up).

fields.activity_title: Fall Salmon (non-Sockeye) Stock Assessment
fields.expected_results: Hupacasath Fisheries provide adult salmon escapement and biological sampling information to DFO for the Sproat and Great Central Lakes systems from early May to early November. Participate in fall salmon stock assessment survey planning with DFO Stock Assessment Biologist Diana McHugh. The Organization and DFO (Diana McHugh) agree to Alberni Inlet and Somass River salmon escapement survey schedule and species priorities. Salmon escapement surveys are completed and results recorded on Stream Inspection Logs (SILs) and sent to DFO (Diana McHugh and the DFO Resource Manager) after each survey is completed. Signed Economic Opportunity Agreement for Somass sockeye, chinook, coho and chum (when abundances are sufficient). Signed ESSR Agreement for surplus Robertson Creek hatchery coho and possibly chinook.
fields.dfo_report: Salmon escapement and biological sampling information provided to DFO (Diana Dobson, Carmen McConnell) on agreed upon schedule (usually by the Wednesday morning of each week). Salmon Escapement Enumeration Survey planning meeting recorded in the Meeting Log in the Program Authority Template provided. Results of the planning including the list of streams to be surveyed and species priorities reported in the Year End Report. Completed SILs are sent to DFO (Diana McHugh and the DFO Resource Manager). Reporting obligations for the Somass Economic Fisheries Agreement are met. Reporting obligations for the Robertson Creek ESSR fishery are met.

fields.task_description: The objective of the program is to estimate salmon escapement using video counts from the Sproat and Stamp Falls fishways. Counting operations at the Sproat and Stamp Falls fishways will begin in mid-May and run through mid-August, depending on environmental conditions. The Organization will provide trained and experienced observers to review a sub-sample of the video from both sites in order to generate estimates of escapement to each system.  The sub-sampling routine will consist of observers reviewing a portion of the minutes of each hour of video footage. These counts will then be expanded to estimate hourly counts. During times of high fish passage, the observers may only review 5, 10, 15, 20, or 30 minutes of each hour in order to keep up-to-date on counts. During periods of slow migration, the observers may review all 60 minutes of each hour. The Organization will identify fish to species and estimate the portion of marked (e.g., adipose fin clipped) fish. Biological samples of salmon are collected 2-3 times per week from fish at both counting sites to estimate the age and sex composition of escapement.

fields.task_description: The objective of the program is to estimate escapement of salmon using video counts from the Sproat and Stamp Falls fishways. Salmon counting operations at the Sproat and Stamp Falls fishways will begin in mid-August and run through mid-November, depending on environmental conditions. The Organization will provide trained and experienced observers to review a sub-sample of the video from both sites in order to generate estimates of escapement to each system. The sub-sampling routine will consist of observers reviewing a portion of the minutes of each hour of video footage. These counts will then be expanded to estimate hourly counts. During times of high fish passage, the observers may only review 5, 10, 15, 20, or 30 minutes of each hour in order to keep up-to-date on counts. During periods of slow migration, the observers may review all 60 minutes of each hour. The Organization will identify fish to species and estimate the portion of marked (e.g., adipose fin clipped) fish. Biological samples of salmon are collected 2-3 times per week from fish at both counting sites to estimate the age and sex composition of Sockeye escapement.

fields.expected_results: The Organization will collect adult salmon escapement and biological sampling information from Sproat and Stamp Rivers. Salmon escapement and biological sampling data will provide information on salmon age, sex and run composition. This work will inform Alberni Inlet Recreational, Commercial, and First Nation fisheries.
fields.dfo_report: Salmon escapement and biological sampling information will be provided to DFO Stock Assessment in the form of Daily Activity Sheets, bypass count sheets, bio-data sheets, and updated escapement counts.

fields.task_description: The objective of the program is to estimate escapement of salmon using video counts from the Sproat and Stamp Falls fishways. Salmon counting operations at the Sproat and Stamp Falls fishways will begin in mid-August and run through mid-November, depending on environmental conditions. The Organization will provide trained and experienced observers to review a sub-sample of the video from both sites in order to generate estimates of escapement to each system. The sub-sampling routine will consist of observers reviewing a portion of the minutes of each hour of video footage. These counts will then be expanded to estimate hourly counts. During times of high fish passage, the observers may only review 5, 10, 15, 20, or 30 minutes of each hour in order to keep up-to-date on counts. During periods of slow migration, the observers may review all 60 minutes of each hour. The Organization will identify fish to species and estimate the portion of marked (e.g., adipose fin clipped) fish. Biological samples of salmon are collected 2-3 times per week from fish at both counting sites to estimate the age and sex composition of Sockeye escapement.
fields.activity_title: Late Summer and Fall Salmon Enumeration at Sproat River and Stamp Fall Fishways
fields.expected_results: The Organization will collect adult salmon escapement and biological sampling information from Sproat and Stamp Rivers. Salmon escapement and biological sampling data will provide information on salmon age, sex and run composition. This work will inform Alberni Inlet Recreational, Commercial, and First Nation fisheries.
fields.dfo_report: Salmon escapement and biological sampling information will be provided to DFO Stock Assessment in the form of Daily Activity Sheets, bypass count sheets, bio-data sheets, and updated escapement counts.

fields.task_description: The cost to run the entire program is $22,000.00; the $11,581.00 will be used to install and get all the traps prepared prior to March 31st. The traps will be in operation until June therefore the rest of the work will be conducted in fiscal year 2021-2022. Smolt Out-Migration through Robertson Creek: Estimates of out-migrating sockeye smolts transiting through Robertson Creek will be generated through daily counts of fish captured in the diversion trap. The site will be visited 7 days per week by Hupacasath Fisheries technicians. During each visit all fish will be identified by species and bulk weights will be taken of the sockeye to determine the average weight. During three visits per week 2 technicians will sample the sockeye smolts. Lengths, weights and scale smears (if requested by DFO) will be taken from sockeye smolts. The target sample size will be 100 smolts per sampling event. Maintenance and adjustment of the stop logs and the debris screens will be completed on each visit to ensure flow through the diversion trap is adequate. These activities will be overseen by a Hupacasath Fisheries Biologist and the data will be shared with DFO as requested. Smolt Out-Migration through Sproat River:Sockeye smolt migration through Sproat River will be conducted in conjunction with the Robertson Creek monitoring. A Rotary Screw Trap (RST) will be installed in the Sproat River above the fishway with the use of a contracted helicopter. 3.The installation of the trap will be completed by Hupacasath Fisheries Technicians with assistance from DFO personnel. Once the trap is installed it will be monitored by Hupacasath technicians. The fish will be counted daily and bulk weights will be taken of sockeye. The target will be 100 samples per week for length and weight measurements unless requested by DFO to collect additional samples.

fields.task_description: 1.Coldwater River Coho: NWSFA will undertake an adult Coho enumeration project at the Coldwater River fence.  The project will involve enumeration by sex, as well as adipose clip and CWT status through the utilization of a trap box and Sonar technology.  CWT status will be assessed by the removal of marked fish for sampling. Fish released upstream of the trap box will be externally marked to determine if fish have been previously handled. This will assist in the calculation of clip rates from upstream sampling efforts as clip rates will change with the removal of clipped fish at the fence.  Specific technical detail of this project can be found in Supplemental Conditions/Provisions for Fiscal Year 2020-2021. 2.Nicola River and tributaries Coho: As time, budget, and weather conditions allow, other known Coho spawning areas will be checked, and counts of adult Coho performed 3 times over the 3 weeks of expected peak spawn:  Nicola River near Dot ranch; upstream of Nicola and Coldwater confluence to Nicola lake dam and upper Nicola River; plus tributaries such as Guichon Creek, Clapperton Creek, Spahomin Creek, Quilchena Creek and Chutter Ranch side channel. 3.Nicola River Chinook:  NWSFA staff will carry out the carcass recovery and sampling work associated with mark/recapture activities.  Carcass recovery activities will be undertaken in the Nicola River mainstem between the outlet of Nicola Lake and the Dot Trestle, lower Clapperton Creek, Coldwater River downstream of the IR#1 bridge, and Spius Creek downstream of Little Box Canyon. If appropriate (budget- and fish-presence dependant), the upper Nicola River between Nicola Lake and Douglas Lake, and Spahomin Creek, will also be inspected. Other possible Chinook refuge habitat will be surveyed as time, budget and weather conditions allow.

fields.dfo_report: 1.A copy of the DFO / Ha'wiih/ Chief and Council approved F&C Fishing Plan and summary of the season's results will be provided to DFO WCVI AFS Manager and the Organization's Central Region Fisheries Biologist. CWT status will be assessed by the removal of marked fish for sampling. Fish released upstream of the trap box will be externally marked to determine if fish have been previously handled. This will assist in the calculation of clip rates from upstream sampling efforts as clip rates will change with the removal of clipped fish at the fence.  Specific technical detail of this project can be found in Supplemental Conditions/Provisions for Fiscal Year 2020-2021. 2.Nicola River and tributaries Coho: As time, budget, and weather conditions allow, other known Coho spawning areas will be checked, and counts of adult Coho performed 3 times over the 3 weeks of expected peak spawn:  Nicola River near Dot ranch; upstream of Nicola and Coldwater confluence to Nicola lake dam and upper Nicola River; plus tributaries such as Guichon Creek, Clapperton Creek, Spahomin Creek, Quilchena Creek and Chutter Ranch side channel. 3.Nicola River Chinook:  NWSFA staff will carry out the carcass recovery and sampling work associated with mark/recapture activities.  Carcass recovery activities will be undertaken in the Nicola River mainstem between the outlet of Nicola Lake and the Dot Trestle, lower Clapperton Creek, Coldwater River downstream of the IR#1 bridge, and Spius Creek downstream of Little Box Canyon. If appropriate (budget- and fish-presence dependant), the upper Nicola River between Nicola Lake and Douglas Lake, and Spahomin Creek, will also be inspected. Other possible Chinook refuge habitat will be surveyed as time, budget and weather conditions allow.
fields.activity_title: Stock Assessment
fields.expected_results: 1.Stock assessment enumeration programs will be carried out by NWSFA following the NTA Stock Assessment Chinook and Coho Protocols and Procedures as outlined in Schedule 5 Supplemental Conditions/Provisions (conditions to be finalized in July 2020) for the Fiscal Year 2020-2021.2.Technical capacity of field crew will be maintained and strengthened through on-going interaction/engagement with a qualified NWSFA staff, as well as site visits by DFO biologists and/or experienced technicians. 3.Community members will be employed (2 to 8 individuals). 4.Stock assessment enumeration program data will be provided to appropriate DFO staff in agreed-upon formats and timelines to support informed fisheries management.
fields.dfo_report: 1.Stock assessment enumeration program data and biological samples will be provided to DFO Stock Assessment staff in Kamloops as outlined in the STC Stock Assessment Chinook and Coho Protocols and Procedures as agreed upon and outlined in Schedule 5 Supplemental Conditions/Provisions for the Fiscal Year 2020-2021.2.A post-season summary of stock assessment activities will be provided in the Year End Report.

fields.task_description: Under contract with the STC, the Siska Band will carry out in-person interviews with fishers to collect Food, Social and Ceremonial (FSC) salmon catch information at Siska fishing sites. Crews will also collect biological samples as agreed to with DFO. Catch data is submitted to DFO weekly.  Meetings occur pre-season with DFO for the purpose of training and in-season to share information, resolve issues of concern and facilitate effective coordination of catch monitoring and fishing activities.Specific tasks will include:1.A catch monitoring schedule will be completed by the Siska Band in collaboration with the NWSFA Fisheries Technologist and DFO.  DFO will lead  orientation(s) for monitors prior to start of the program which may include a site visit to fishing areas.2.Monitors will carry out the field data collection according to schedule and will report missed shifts or changes to the schedule to the Fisheries Technologist (or a designated NWSFA alternate staff as agreed to with DFO). The Fisheries Technologist (or alternate) will update DFO as soon as possible to enable schedule modification. Any conservation and protection concerns that monitors have during their shift will be reported to the Fisheries Technologist (or alternate) who will contact the appropriate DFO staff as soon as possible.3.During the program, the NWSFA Fisheries Technologist will verify that the data sheets match the schedule and will coordinate with Siska and/or DFO to address data quality concerns in-season.
fields.element_title: Food, Social and Ceremonial (FSC) Fisheries Management
fields.activity_title: FSC Catch Monitoring (Siska)

fields.task_description: Top up Key Element A/Activity 2: Stock Assessment Coldwater River Coho and Nicola River and Tributaries Coho. Increase the number of days for rental of security fencing and field office, and contribute to extending the number of days we have staff on site for fence/trap operations (wages). Increased funds will also be utilized to conduct a carcass recovery assessment and allow for necessary travel.
fields.activity_title: Coldwater River Coho and Nicola River and Tributaries Coho

fields.task_description: Top up Key Element A/Activity 2: Stock Assessment Nicola River Chinook. Additional funds will allow for full implementation of the Nicola chinook carcass recovery program.
fields.activity_title: Nicola River Chinook

fields.task_description: 1.Ahousaht Fisheries staff conducts escapement surveys according to a survey schedule developed with Ahousaht Fisheries, the Organization�s Central Region Fisheries Biologist, the Ahousaht/ Fish Farm Enhancement Committee, and with DFO South Coast Stock Assessment staff. 2.With the assistance of external funding from Canadian Food Inspection Agency (CFIA), Ahousaht Fisheries staff conducts bio-toxin monitoring.  AFS funding pays for Ahousaht Fisheries staff wages and related expenses to assist with the monitoring.  CFIA funding pays for Ahousaht Fisheries boat operating expenses and shipping of samples.3.Ahousaht Fisheries conduct general monitoring, and biological and enforcement surveys of Ahousaht Ha-houlthee and report issues or concerns to the community and relevant agencies.
fields.activity_title: Stock Assessment and Fisheries Management- Ahousaht

fields.expected_results: 1.FSC Salmon Catch data for areas designated in Metlakatla's asserted traditional territory will be collected and stored in a database, copies of which will be provided to DFO AFS Resource Manager monthly to assist in Fisheries Resource Management decision-making.  Final catch numbers submitted by November 15 (prior to final report).2.The Organization's fishery is coordinated, managed and monitored in accordance with Schedule A of this Agreement.
fields.dfo_report: 1.Catch and Fishery Monitoring records will be provided in electronic form to the DFO AFS Resource Manager by mid-November.2.Summary of the annual FSC Harvests. This report will be included in the Year End Report (Schedule 7).

fields.activity_title: Stock Assessment and Fisheries Management- Ahousaht
fields.expected_results: 1.Conduct escapement surveys on the Atleo, Bawden Creek, Hootla Kootla, Ice, Upper Megin and Whitepine Rivers. 2.Conduct CFIA bio-toxin sampling weekly from May to October and bi-weekly from November to April. 3.Conduct six or more general monitoring surveys (e.g., sea-lice, clam, sea otters) and six or more enforcement surveys (e.g., recreational fisheries or food fishery) and other surveys (e.g., herring) as contracted by DFO (if applicable).  When a specific DFO survey contract is awarded, the report on surveys will distinguish AFS funded activities versus non-AFS funded activities. 4.Monitor the environment in Ahousaht Ha-houlthee and report concerns to community and appropriate agency staff such as Ministry of Environment, DFO, etc.
fields.dfo_report: 1.Results of escapement surveys on Stream Inspection Log reports will be provided to DFO Stock Assessment, cc DFO WCVI AFS Manager in-season.  The actual dates and method of reporting to DFO will be included in the AFS Year End Report.2.Samples are sent to CFIA weekly from May to October and bi-weekly from November to April via pre-paid courier. Provide dates and method of submission to CFIA in the AFS Year End Report.3.Summary of survey and monitoring results to relevant DFO staff and DFO WCVI AFS Manager, and listed in the AFS Year End Report.4.Relevant information about the environment and species in Ahousaht Ha-houlthee will be reported to the appropriate DFO staff in-season and summarized in the Year End Report.

fields.activity_title: Stock Assessment and Fisheries Management-Ditidaht
fields.expected_results: 1.Conduct escapement surveys according to survey schedule developed with DFO StAD and Ditidaht Fisheries staff a.Install and operate a counting fence on the Hobiton River from late April to June (river level dependent) to enumerate returning adult sockeye.  b.Assess and prepare new juvenile downstream Rotary Screw Trap site on Hobiton River in April/May 2021. c.Conduct escapement surveys on the Cheewaht River in October and November d.Conduct assessment test fisheries for chinook, chum and coho in Nitinat Lake from August to November 2.Conduct monitoring and assessments for Nitinat Lake crab at least six times throughout the year.3. Continue to develop a monitoring and assessment program for groundfish using long-line surveys techniques in DFO Statistical Areas 21/121.4.Marine bio-toxins are monitored weekly from May to October for CFIA.5.Monitor the environment in the area and report concerns to community and appropriate agency staff such as Ministry of Environment, DFO, etc. (e.g., bridge and culvert crossing during heavy rain events along the Carmanah Main, sediment traps in the Cheewaht watershed).6.Assist Nitinat hatchery staff with specific activities (e.g., chinook, chum brood-stock collections, provide staff and vessels for feeding net pen chinook, assist Nitinat hatchery staff in release of juvenile salmon).7.Development of an ESSR Agreement for Nitinat Lake chinook, coho and chum. Ditidaht Fisheries Program staff and the Organization's Southern Region Fisheries Biologist will work with DFO Nitinat Enhancement Facility Manager and DFO WCVI AFS Manager, in August.8.Participate in fall salmon stock assessment survey planning with DFO Stock Assessment Biologist.
fields.dfo_report: 1.Escapement survey results are provided to DFO South Coast Stock Assessment in season and to the DFO WCVI AFS Manager in the AFS Year End Report including:a. Hobiton River adult sockeye enumeration results including dates of Hobiton fence operation, daily escapement data and bio-sampling. The actual dates and method of reporting to DFO will be included in the AFS Year End Report. b.Digital results of juvenile tapping on the Hobiton River reported at the end of trapping operations including dates fished, daily counts by species and bio-samples. The actual dates and method of reporting to DFO will be included in the AFS Year End Report.c.Salmon Escapement Enumeration Survey results will be reported on Stream Inspection Logs (SILs) in-season. The actual dates and method of reporting to DFO will be included in the AFS Year End Report. d.Reports summarizing Nitinat Lake salmon assessment activities including abundance and biosampling data, submitted to, Nitinat River Enhancement Facility Manager and as defined above. The actual dates and method of reporting to DFO will be included in the AFS Year End Report.2.Reports summarising crab assessment activities including biosampling data, detailed catch and effort submitted electronically (Word, Excel files as appropriate) in the AFS Year End Report.3.Results from the groundfish survey(s) (survey design, sampling procedures, sampling dates, location, survey catch results, species, weight, etc.) will be submitted electronically (Word, Excel files as appropriate) in the AFS Year End Report 4.Biotoxin monitoring samples are sent to CFIA weekly from May to October via pre-paid courier. Provide date and method of submission to CFIA in the AFS Year End Report.5.Summary of monitoring concerns and resulting referrals will be included in the AFS Year End Report including which agency and contact the concerns were delivered to. 6.Summary of number of employees assisting Nitinat hatchery and list of activities they were involved with, to be included in the AFS Year End Report. 7.Signed ESSR Agreement and a report of all catch by species, number sold, etc. will be provided to DFO WCVI AFS Manager as per the agreed upon in-season catch reporting schedule. Provide date and method of submission to DFO in the AFS Year End Report.8. Salmon Escapement Enumeration Survey planning results and decisions will be provided in the AFS Year End Report.

Continue to develop a monitoring and assessment program for groundfish using long-line surveys techniques in DFO Statistical Areas 21/121.4.Marine bio-toxins are monitored weekly from May to October for CFIA.5.Monitor the environment in the area and report concerns to community and appropriate agency staff such as Ministry of Environment, DFO, etc. (e.g., bridge and culvert crossing during heavy rain events along the Carmanah Main, sediment traps in the Cheewaht watershed).6.Assist Nitinat hatchery staff with specific activities (e.g., chinook, chum brood-stock collections, provide staff and vessels for feeding net pen chinook, assist Nitinat hatchery staff in release of juvenile salmon).7.Development of an ESSR Agreement for Nitinat Lake chinook, coho and chum. Ditidaht Fisheries Program staff and the Organization's Southern Region Fisheries Biologist will work with DFO Nitinat Enhancement Facility Manager and DFO WCVI AFS Manager, in August.8.Participate in fall salmon stock assessment survey planning with DFO Stock Assessment Biologist.
fields.dfo_report: 1.Escapement survey results are provided to DFO South Coast Stock Assessment in season and to the DFO WCVI AFS Manager in the AFS Year End Report including:a. Hobiton River adult sockeye enumeration results including dates of Hobiton fence operation, daily escapement data and bio-sampling. The actual dates and method of reporting to DFO will be included in the AFS Year End Report. b.Digital results of juvenile tapping on the Hobiton River reported at the end of trapping operations including dates fished, daily counts by species and bio-samples. The actual dates and method of reporting to DFO will be included in the AFS Year End Report.c.Salmon Escapement Enumeration Survey results will be reported on Stream Inspection Logs (SILs) in-season. The actual dates and method of reporting to DFO will be included in the AFS Year End Report. d.Reports summarizing Nitinat Lake salmon assessment activities including abundance and biosampling data, submitted to, Nitinat River Enhancement Facility Manager and as defined above. The actual dates and method of reporting to DFO will be included in the AFS Year End Report.2.Reports summarising crab assessment activities including biosampling data, detailed catch and effort submitted electronically (Word, Excel files as appropriate) in the AFS Year End Report.3.Results from the groundfish survey(s) (survey design, sampling procedures, sampling dates, location, survey catch results, species, weight, etc.) will be submitted electronically (Word, Excel files as appropriate) in the AFS Year End Report 4.Biotoxin monitoring samples are sent to CFIA weekly from May to October via pre-paid courier. Provide date and method of submission to CFIA in the AFS Year End Report.5.Summary of monitoring concerns and resulting referrals will be included in the AFS Year End Report including which agency and contact the concerns were delivered to. 6.Summary of number of employees assisting Nitinat hatchery and list of activities they were involved with, to be included in the AFS Year End Report. 7.Signed ESSR Agreement and a report of all catch by species, number sold, etc. will be provided to DFO WCVI AFS Manager as per the agreed upon in-season catch reporting schedule. Provide date and method of submission to DFO in the AFS Year End Report.8. Salmon Escapement Enumeration Survey planning results and decisions will be provided in the AFS Year End Report.

fields.task_description: 1.Ehattesaht Fisheries staff conduct salmon and herring spawning surveys according to survey schedule developed with the Organization's Northern Region Fisheries Biologist and DFO South Coast Stock Assessment (for salmon surveys) as follows: a.Enumerate adult Tahtahtis (Zeballos) River hinkuuas (chum salmon) in September to mid-October by conducting weekly bank or snorkel counts to enumerate spawning salmon from the municipal campground at tidewater to and including the canyon tail spawning bed.  Observation data will be reported to DFO South Coast Stock Assessment  (cc DFO WCVI AFS Manager) on Stream Inspection Logs in-season.  The actual dates and method of reporting to DFO will be included in the AFS Year End Report.b.Ehattesaht staff will work with the Organization's staff to monitor herring spawn distribution, and any food and ceremonial herring fisheries in northern DFO Statistical Area 25.2.Ehattesaht Fisheries staff conduct general monitoring of Ehattesaht Ha-houlthee and report issues or concerns to the community and relevant agencies.3.Ehatteshat Fisheries staff conduct a feasibility study on restoring access for salmon above Zeballos River cascade or falls.4.Ehattesaht Fisheries staff participate in the operation of the Zeballos River hatchery and work closely with the DFO Community Advisor, members of the Zeballos Enhancement Society, youth and community members performing various activities (e.g., salmon broodstock collections, egg incubation, juvenile salmon rearing and releases and may participate in the future in feeding of net penned chum and other species as approved by DFO).5. Ehattesaht Fisheries staff participate in juvenile Chinook salmon micro-trolling sampling activities coordinated through DFO Science (Jessy Bokvist) including all required sampling protocol training.

fields.activity_title: Stock Assessment and Fisheries Management- Ehattesaht
fields.expected_results: 1.Conduct salmon escapement surveys on the Tahtahtis (Zeballos) River from September to late fall and monitor herring spawn deposition and fisheries in February and March.2.Issues or concerns related to fishing, fish and fish habitat are reported to the Council, community and relevant agencies.3. Ehattesaht Fisheries staff participate on a feasibility study to restore access for salmon above the Zeballos River cascade or falls in the canyon affected by Forest Service Road construction if funded by external sources. 4.Participation, including Ehattesaht students and youth, in the operation of the Zeballos River salmon hatchery including (but not limited to) brood-stock collection, fish husbandry and fry release. 5.Staff and youth will participate in all required protocol training and up to ten days of micro-trolling sampling for juvenile Chinook salmon during October-March period.
fields.dfo_report: 1.Results of escapement surveys according to survey schedules as follows:a.Salmon Escapement Enumeration Survey results including dates of snorkel survey results will be put on Stream Inspection Logs and bio-samples are provided to DFO Stock Assessment (cc DFO WCVI AFS Manager) in-season. The actual dates and method of reporting to DFO will be included in the Third Quarter and AFS Year End Report. 2.Summary of monitoring concerns and resulting referrals will be included in the AFS Year End Report including which agency and contact the concerns were delivered to.3.Summary of the status of the Zeballos River salmon access improvements feasibility, and resulting referrals will be included in the AFS Year End Report including to which agency and contact person the concerns were delivered.4. Summary of number of youth and volunteers assisting with each of the Tahtahtis (Zeballos) River hatchery activities they were involved with, to be included in the AFS Year End Report. Description of hatchery activities by Ehattesaht Fisheries program staff will also be included in AFS Year End Report.5. Summary of AFS funded Ehattesaht Fisheries staff activities and Ehattesaht youth's participation in micro-trolling activities will be reported in the AFS Year End Report as well as all required reporting/deliverables to DFO Science.

fields.task_description: 1.Hesquiaht Fisheries staff conduct salmon escapement surveys. 2.Hesquiaht Fisheries staff will construct new or re-establish old trails alongside some of the streams that will undergo salmon escapement surveys.   3.Hesquiaht Fisheries staff will conduct general monitoring and biological surveys of Hesquiaht Ha-houlthee. 4.Hesquiaht Fisheries will continue to work with Central Westcoast Forest Society (CWFS) on stream restoration work for Ay-yi-sagh Creek, the extent of work completed will be dependent on external funding.  AFS funding pays for Hesquiaht Fisheries staff wages and related expenses, if funding is not available through CWFS.  CWFS pays for any other expenditures required for the project.  Hesquiaht Fisheries only participates in the work if funding is available by CWFS.5. Hesquiaht Fisheries staff will support the construction and installation of a counting fence at Purdon Creek and Hisnit Lake to enumerate adult salmon escapement.

fields.activity_title: Stock Assessment and Fisheries Management- Hesquiaht
fields.expected_results: 1.Conduct escapement surveys for coho and chum on Ah'ta'apq, Tsa-ya, Sachie, Ay-yi-sagh, Yaaksis, Maahpe, Purdon, Tsa-Aio and Teamut streams according to a survey schedule developed with the NTC biologist, DFO South Coast Stock Assessment staff and Hesquiaht Fisheries.2.Construct or re-establish and maintain one or more trails alongside a stream scheduled to undergo salmon escapements surveys.3. Conduct one or more assessments such as herring spawn, sea otter, crab, geoduck or clam surveys in Hesquiaht Ha-houlthee.4.Conduct one or more stream restoration projects in Hesquiaht Ha-houlthee, dependant on external funding.5.Support from the Hesquiaht Fisheries staff to construct and install as well as operate fish fences on Purdon Creek and Hisnit Lake for the collection of salmon escapement data.  Data provided to DFO South Coast Stock Assessment and DFO AFS Manager at the end of the project.
fields.dfo_report: 1.Results of salmon escapement surveys using Stream Inspection Logs provided to DFO Stock Assessment (cc DFO WCVI AFS Manager) in-season. The actual dates and method of reporting to DFO will be included in the AFS Year End Report.2.Summary of results maintaining trail access in support of salmon escapement surveys will be included in the AFS Year End Report (at least two photos will be included). 3.Summary of survey and monitoring (i.e. fish fence counts) results provided to relevant DFO staff (cc DFO WCVI AFS Manager) and dates and results of survey listed in AFS Year End Report. 4.AFS Year End Report will include a brief update on stream restoration projects.5.Salmon Escapement Enumeration Survey results will be provided in the AFS Year End Report.

Data provided to DFO South Coast Stock Assessment and DFO AFS Manager at the end of the project.
fields.dfo_report: 1.Results of salmon escapement surveys using Stream Inspection Logs provided to DFO Stock Assessment (cc DFO WCVI AFS Manager) in-season. The actual dates and method of reporting to DFO will be included in the AFS Year End Report.2.Summary of results maintaining trail access in support of salmon escapement surveys will be included in the AFS Year End Report (at least two photos will be included). 3.Summary of survey and monitoring (i.e. fish fence counts) results provided to relevant DFO staff (cc DFO WCVI AFS Manager) and dates and results of survey listed in AFS Year End Report. 4.AFS Year End Report will include a brief update on stream restoration projects.5.Salmon Escapement Enumeration Survey results will be provided in the AFS Year End Report.

fields.task_description: 1.Hesquiaht Fisheries staff conduct salmon escapement surveys. 2.Hesquiaht Fisheries staff will construct new or re-establish old trails alongside some of the streams that will undergo salmon escapement surveys.   3.Hesquiaht Fisheries staff will conduct general monitoring and biological surveys of Hesquiaht Ha-houlthee. 4.Hesquiaht Fisheries will continue to work with Central Westcoast Forest Society (CWFS) on stream restoration work for Ay-yi-sagh Creek, the extent of work completed will be dependent on external funding.  AFS funding pays for Hesquiaht Fisheries staff wages and related expenses, if funding is not available through CWFS.  CWFS pays for any other expenditures required for the project.  Hesquiaht Fisheries only participates in the work if funding is available by CWFS.5. Hesquiaht Fisheries staff will support the construction and installation of a counting fence at Purdon Creek and Hisnit Lake to enumerate adult salmon escapement.

fields.task_description: 1.Mowachaht/Muchalaht Fisheries staff conducts escapement surveys according to survey schedule developed with Uu-a-thluk Regional Biologist and DFO South Coast Stock Assessment staff. a.Enumerate Oktwanch River (Gold River) sockeye and Chinook at Burman River, visual surveys (2-3 surveys) from September to November. b.Mowachaht/Muchalaht Fisheries staff will implement a bus route CREEL monitoring program for Gold River sockeye fisheries to estimate catch and effort by seine, dipnet and hook and line.2.With the assistance of external funding from the Canada Food Inspection Agency (CFIA), Mowachaht/Muchalaht Fisheries staff conduct bio-toxin monitoring from May to October. 3. Mowachaht/Muchalaht Fisheries staff conduct general monitoring of Mowachaht/Muchalaht Ha-houlthee and report issues or concerns to the community and relevant agencies.4. Mowachaht/Muchalaht Fisheries staff works closely with the Nootka Sound Watershed Society (NSWS) and Conuma hatchery staff (e.g., salmon collections, juvenile salmon releases and feeding net pen chinook and chum).5.Mowachaht/Muchalaht Fisheries staff work with DFO and the Organization's staff on the planning and development of an Excess Salmon to Spawning Requirements (ESSR) agreement for Conuma River chinook, coho and chum if abundances are deemed sufficient.6.Mowachaht/Muchalaht Fisheries staff works with DFO to coordinate for fall salmon stock assessment survey planning and information flow.
fields.activity_title: Stock Assessment and Fisheries Management- Mowachaht/Muchalaht
fields.expected_results: 1.Conduct escapement surveys for coho and chum on Ah'ta'apq, Tsa-ya, Sachie, Ay-yi-sagh, Yaaksis, Maahpe, Purdon, Tsa-Aio and Teamut streams according to a survey schedule developed with the NTC biologist, DFO South Coast Stock Assessment staff and Hesquiaht Fisheries.2.Construct or re-establish and maintain one or more trails alongside a stream scheduled to undergo salmon escapements surveys.3. Conduct one or more assessments such as herring spawn, sea otter, crab, geoduck or clam surveys in Hesquiaht Ha-houlthee.4.Conduct one or more stream restoration projects in Hesquiaht Ha-houlthee, dependant on external funding.5.Support from the Hesquiaht Fisheries staff to construct and install as well as operate fish fences on Purdon Creek and Hisnit Lake for the collection of salmon escapement data.  Data provided to DFO South Coast Stock Assessment and DFO AFS Manager at the end of the project.

fields.activity_title: Stock Assessment and Fisheries Management- Mowachaht/Muchalaht
fields.expected_results: 1.Salmon escapement survey work by the Mowachaht/Muchalaht Fisheries staff includes:a.Conducting escapement surveys for sockeye salmon on the Oktwanch River (Gold) from September to early November.b.Conducting a bus route survey for Oktwanch River (Gold River) sockeye fisheries c. Supporting contracted escapement projects with DFO StAD tentatively identified at Tsowwin, Canton, and Oktwanch and Burman Rivers. d.Supporting Conuma Chinook mark-recapture2.Marine bio-toxins are monitored weekly from May to October for CFIA.3.Monitor the environment in the Mowachaht/ Muchalaht Ha-houlthee and report concerns to community and appropriate agency staff such Environment & Climate Change Canada, DFO, Province of BC Forest, Lands and Natural Resource Operations and Rural Development, etc. (e.g., derelict float homes, logging erosion, rate of cut considerations affecting salmon production).4. Assist Nootka Sound Watershed Society (NSWS) with activities in relation to production Chinook from the Gold and Burman Rivers satellite programs with Conuma hatchery (e.g., Chinook, chum and brood-stock collections, biosampling provide NSWS assistance for feeding net pen Chinook, assist Conuma hatchery staff in release of juvenile salmon) and participate in the annual production planning for Conuma hatchery with DFO SEP staff 5.Development of an ESSR Agreement for Conuma Chinook, Coho and Chum. Mowachaht/Muchalaht Fisheries program staff and the Organization's Northern Region Fisheries Biologist will work with Conuma DFO enhancement Facility Manager and DFO WCVI AFS Manager in August.6.Participate in juvenile fall salmon stock assessment survey planning with DFO Stock Assessment Biologist.
fields.dfo_report: 1.Results of escapement surveys according to survey schedules as follows:a.Oktwanch and Burman rivers Salmon Escapement Enumeration Survey results will be reported to DFO South Coast Stock Assessment Biologist (cc DFO WCVI AFS Manager) on Stream Inspection Logs in-season.  The actual dates and method of reporting to DFO will be included in the AFS Year End Report.b.Reports summarizing CREEL results including effort, catch and gear type, provided to DFO South Coast Stock Assessment (cc DFO WCVI AFS Manager) in-season. The actual dates and method of reporting to DFO will be included in the AFS Year End Report.2.Samples are sent to CFIA weekly from May to October via pre-paid courier. Provide date and method of submission to CFIA in the AFS Year End Report.3.Summary of monitoring concerns and resulting referrals will be included in the AFS Year End Report including which agency and contact the concerns were delivered to.4.Summary of number of employees assisting Conuma hatchery and list of activities they were involved with, to be included in the AFS Year End Report.5.Summary of Mowachaht/Muchalaht priorities and  recommendations regarding Conuma hatchery production planning and other salmon enhancement efforts for Area 25 will be provided to DFO SEP through production planning process.6.Signed ESSR Agreement (if viable ESSR opportunity develops) and completion of all catch reporting requirements  provided to DFO Resource Manager (Amy Greenwood) weekly. Provide date and method of submission to DFO in the AFS Year End Report.7.Salmon Escapement Enumeration Survey planning results and decisions will be provided in the AFS Year End Report.

fields.task_description: 1.Nuchatlaht Fisheries staff will monitor, sound, and survey herring spawning waters.2.Nuchatlaht Fisheries staff will monitor and survey spawning streams for salmon.  Reporting live count and carcasses on 2 streams: Espinosa, Savey Creek (Owossista, and Mary Basin, if conditions permit). 3.Nuchatlaht staff will monitor spawning waters for both herring and salmon for activities that may impact spawning areas, such as upland activity disturbances that may affect water, sediment and large wood debris, cover in the "shore zone," and/or sedimentation of salmon spawning habitat.4.Nuchatlaht staff will plan protections for estuaries and watersheds from industrial activities in the form of Salmon Forest Conservation Areas in the Owiissta/Apple Creeks and the Shoomaht/Ransom Creek (Nuu-chah-nulth Salmon Forest Ecological Network watersheds).
fields.activity_title: Stock Assessment and Fisheries Management- Nuchatlaht

fields.task_description: 1.Tla-o-qui-aht Fisheries staff support the Salmon Enhancement Program to rehabilitate salmon stocks and key habitat in the Kennedy watershed.2.Tla-o-qui-aht Fisheries staff monitor and conduct escapement surveys according to survey schedule developed with Tla-o-qui-aht Fisheries staff, the Organization's Central Region Fisheries biologist and DFO South Coast Stock Assessment.3.Tla-o-qui-aht Fisheries conduct general monitoring and surveying of Tla-o-qui-aht Ha-houlthee and report issues or concerns to the community and relevant agencies.
fields.activity_title: Stock Assessment and Fisheries Management- Tla-o-qui-aht
fields.expected_results: 1.Conduct broodstock capture in the Upper Kennedy River. Training of hatchery staff, dealing with the fertilization, incubation and rearing of chinook eggs and fry.2.Plan to expand Tla-o-qui-aht's hatchery operations by investigating the feasibility of other enhancement sites and enhancement of other species (i.e. Sockeye). This will be done in conjunction with Kennedy Watershed Sockeye restoration planning.3.Conduct and/or assist with escapement surveys according to survey schedule developed with DFO and Tla-o-qui-aht Fisheries staff on Kennedy River systems (i.e. Muriel Lake, Staghorn Creek, Angora Creek and Lower Kennedy and Kennedy Lake).4.Conduct three or more general monitoring surveys (e.g. sea otters) and other surveys as contracted by DFO (if applicable). Monitor the environment in Tla-o-qui-aht Ha-houlthee and report concerns to community and appropriate agency staff such as Ministry of Environment and DFO.  When a specific DFO survey contract is awarded, the report on surveys will distinguish AFS funded activities versus non-AFS funded activities.
fields.dfo_report: 1.Summary of broodstock capture dates and activities supporting SEP activities in the Kennedy watershed will be included in the AFS Year End Report2. The progress on Tla-o-qui-aht's hatchery operations will be summarized in AFS Year End Report. 3.Salmon Escapement Enumeration Survey results will be reported to DFO Stock Assessment (cc DFO WCVI AFS Manager) and DFO Community Advisor on SILs, in-season, according to survey schedule developed with DFO and Tla-o-qui-aht via pre-paid priority post envelopes provided by DFO. The actual dates and method of reporting to DFO will be included in the AFS Year End Report.4.Summary of results will be included in the AFS Year End Report. 5.Summary of survey and monitoring results to relevant DFO staff (cc WCVI AFS Manager), and dates and results of survey listed in AFS Year End Report. (e.g., sea otter survey information will be reported to DFO Science Branch, in-season and summarized in the AFS Year End Report).

Provide date and method of submission to DFO in AFS Year End Report. 2.Catch monitoring results, scheduled reporting of F&C landings and released fish provided to DFO WCVI AFS Manager and the Organization's Southern Region Fisheries Biologist using the Catch Reporting Template provided by NTC as follows:a.Barkley and Fraser Sockeye -Weekly on the Wednesday of each week, during the fishery.b.Nitinat Chinook - Weekly on the Tuesday of each week, during the fishery.c.Nitinat Coho and Chum - On the last day of each month, during the fishery.d.All ocean salmon will be recorded by month and reported on September 30, December 1 and April 8, 2022.e.Groundfish - All groundfish catch to date will be reported on September 30, December 1 and April 8, 2021.Shellfish - All shellfish will be reported on September 30, December 1 and April 8, 2022.g.Herring will be reported by April 8.h.Harvests by a commercial fishing vessel on a dual fishing trip or a contracted fishing trip will be reported within 24 hours after landing.i.In season management - provide DFO updated catch reporting when there is a need to assess supplemental harvest requests.

fields.task_description: 1.Ditidaht will ensure required maintenance for their 2015 Ford F-350 is complete2.Ditidaht will ensure fisheries fieldwork gear is repaired (seine net) or replaced (groundfish gear)3.Ditidaht will purchase a gill net4.Ditidaht will enroll in Office Administration training for Fisheries Managers as well as MED and SRT1 (Marine basic first aid and Swiftwater) training courses for Fisheries technicians.
fields.activity_title: Operational Capacity Funding - Patrol Boat equipment replacement/maintenance and training (capital acquisition and capacity support)-Ditidaht

fields.activity_title: Operational Capacity Funding - Repair and upgrade community hatchery (capital infrustructure and capacity support)-Ehattesaht

fields.task_description: 1.Hesquiaht will replace two computers in their fisheries office with appropriate laptops and software to support fisheries program office work, including allowing for remote video conferencing participation in meetings.2.Hesquiaht will purchase two 150 HP outboards to replace existing 300 HP single outboard 3.Hesquiaht will purchase an ATV for Fisheries Technician use
fields.activity_title: Operational Capacity Funding - Acquisition of office equipment, outboard motors and ATV (capital acquisition)-Hesquiaht

fields.task_description: Nuchatlaht will purchase a Steel warehouse building including overseeing the planning, development and construction phases.

fields.activity_title: Operational Capacity Funding - Patrol Boat equipment and life raft (capital acquisition)- Ahousaht

fields.task_description: 1.Ahousaht Fisheries staff conducts escapement surveys according to a survey schedule developed with Ahousaht Fisheries, the Organization�s Central Region Fisheries Biologist, the Ahousaht/ Fish Farm Enhancement Committee, and with DFO South Coast Stock Assessment staff. 2.With the assistance of external funding from Canadian Food Inspection Agency (CFIA), Ahousaht Fisheries staff conducts bio-toxin monitoring.  AFS funding pays for Ahousaht Fisheries staff wages and related expenses to assist with the monitoring.  CFIA funding pays for Ahousaht Fisheries boat operating expenses and shipping of samples.3.Ahousaht Fisheries conduct general monitoring, and biological and enforcement surveys of Ahousaht Ha-houlthee and report issues or concerns to the community and relevant agencies.
fields.activity_title: Stock Assessment and Fisheries Management- Ahousaht
fields.expected_results: 1.Conduct escapement surveys on the Atleo, Bawden Creek, Hootla Kootla, Ice, Upper Megin and Whitepine Rivers. 2.Conduct CFIA bio-toxin sampling weekly from May to October and bi-weekly from November to April. 3.Conduct six or more general monitoring surveys (e.g., sea-lice, clam, sea otters) and six or more enforcement surveys (e.g., recreational fisheries or food fishery) and other surveys (e.g., herring) as contracted by DFO (if applicable).  When a specific DFO survey contract is awarded, the report on surveys will distinguish AFS funded activities versus non-AFS funded activities. 4.Monitor the environment in Ahousaht Ha-houlthee and report concerns to community and appropriate agency staff such as Ministry of Environment, DFO, etc.
fields.dfo_report: 1.Results of escapement surveys on Stream Inspection Log reports will be provided to DFO Stock Assessment, cc DFO WCVI AFS Manager in-season.  The actual dates and method of reporting to DFO will be included in the AFS Year End Report.2.Samples are sent to CFIA weekly from May to October and bi-weekly from November to April via pre-paid courier. Provide dates and method of submission to CFIA in the AFS Year End Report.3.Summary of survey and monitoring results to relevant DFO staff and DFO WCVI AFS Manager, and listed in the AFS Year End Report.4.Relevant information about the environment and species in Ahousaht Ha-houlthee will be reported to the appropriate DFO staff in-season and summarized in the Year End Report.

fields.task_description: 1.Ditidaht Fisheries staff conducts escapement surveys according to survey schedule developed with DFO South Coast Stock Assessment and Ditidaht. a.Enumerate adult Hobiton River sockeye by installing and operating an adult salmon counting fence from April to June. b.Prepare the juvenile trap site and install Rotary Screw Trap (provided by DFO) with assistance from DFO South Coast Stock Assessment and Uu-a-thluk staff. c.Two to three Cheewaht salmon spawner surveys will occur from October to November. d.Nitinat Lake assessment fisheries:  using food and ceremonial fisheries and Nitinat hatchery chinook, chum and coho broodstock collections to gather information with DFO on run-timing, distribution and age structure of chinook, coho and chum returning to Nitinat Lake from August to November. AFS covers the wages of the Fisheries Manager and some boat and other equipment expenses.  Ditidaht uses internal funding to cover all other costs. 2.Nitinat Lake crab are monitored and assessed at least six times throughout the year.3.Ditidaht staff will work with the Organization's staff to develop and implement groundfish monitoring and assessment in DFO Statistical Areas 21/121.4.With the assistance of external funding from the Canada Food Inspection Agency (CFIA), Ditidaht Fisheries staff conducts bio-toxin monitoring from May to October. AFS funding pays for Ditidaht Fisheries staff wages and related expenses to assist with the monitoring.  CFIA funding pays for Ditidaht Fisheries boat operating expenses and shipping of samples.5.Ditidaht Fisheries conduct general monitoring of Ditidaht Ha-houlthee and report issues or concerns to the community and relevant agencies.6.Ditidaht Fisheries staff works closely with the Nitinat hatchery staff with activities (e.g., salmon broodstock collections, towing net-pens, feeding net penned fish, etc). 7.Ditidaht Fisheries work with DFO and the Organization's staff to develop an Escapement Salmon Spawning Requirements (ESSR) agreement for Nitinat Lake chinook, coho and chum, where abundances are appropriate.8.Ditidaht Fisheries staff work with DFO for fall salmon stock assessment survey planning.

fields.task_description: 1.Ditidaht Fisheries staff conducts escapement surveys according to survey schedule developed with DFO South Coast Stock Assessment and Ditidaht. a.Enumerate adult Hobiton River sockeye by installing and operating an adult salmon counting fence from April to June. b.Prepare the juvenile trap site and install Rotary Screw Trap (provided by DFO) with assistance from DFO South Coast Stock Assessment and Uu-a-thluk staff. c.Two to three Cheewaht salmon spawner surveys will occur from October to November. d.Nitinat Lake assessment fisheries:  using food and ceremonial fisheries and Nitinat hatchery chinook, chum and coho broodstock collections to gather information with DFO on run-timing, distribution and age structure of chinook, coho and chum returning to Nitinat Lake from August to November. AFS covers the wages of the Fisheries Manager and some boat and other equipment expenses.  Ditidaht uses internal funding to cover all other costs. 2.Nitinat Lake crab are monitored and assessed at least six times throughout the year.3.Ditidaht staff will work with the Organization's staff to develop and implement groundfish monitoring and assessment in DFO Statistical Areas 21/121.4.With the assistance of external funding from the Canada Food Inspection Agency (CFIA), Ditidaht Fisheries staff conducts bio-toxin monitoring from May to October. fields.task_description: 1.Ehattesaht Fisheries staff conduct salmon and herring spawning surveys according to survey schedule developed with the Organization's Northern Region Fisheries Biologist and DFO South Coast Stock Assessment (for salmon surveys) as follows: a.Enumerate adult Tahtahtis (Zeballos) River hinkuuas (chum salmon) in September to mid-October by conducting weekly bank or snorkel counts to enumerate spawning salmon from the municipal campground at tidewater to and including the canyon tail spawning bed.  Observation data will be reported to DFO South Coast Stock Assessment  (cc DFO WCVI AFS Manager) on Stream Inspection Logs in-season.  The actual dates and method of reporting to DFO will be included in the AFS Year End Report.b.Ehattesaht staff will work with the Organization's staff to monitor herring spawn distribution, and any food and ceremonial herring fisheries in northern DFO Statistical Area 25.2.Ehattesaht Fisheries staff conduct general monitoring of Ehattesaht Ha-houlthee and report issues or concerns to the community and relevant agencies.3.Ehatteshat Fisheries staff conduct a feasibility study on restoring access for salmon above Zeballos River cascade or falls.4.Ehattesaht Fisheries staff participate in the operation of the Zeballos River hatchery and work closely with the DFO Community Advisor, members of the Zeballos Enhancement Society, youth and community members performing various activities (e.g., salmon broodstock collections, egg incubation, juvenile salmon rearing and releases and may participate in the future in feeding of net penned chum and other species as approved by DFO).5. Ehattesaht Fisheries staff participate in juvenile Chinook salmon micro-trolling sampling activities coordinated through DFO Science (Jessy Bokvist) including all required sampling protocol training.

fields.activity_title: Stock Assessment and Fisheries Management- Ehattesaht
fields.expected_results: 1.Conduct salmon escapement surveys on the Tahtahtis (Zeballos) River from September to late fall and monitor herring spawn deposition and fisheries in February and March.2.Issues or concerns related to fishing, fish and fish habitat are reported to the Council, community and relevant agencies.3. Ehattesaht Fisheries staff participate on a feasibility study to restore access for salmon above the Zeballos River cascade or falls in the canyon affected by Forest Service Road construction if funded by external sources. 4.Participation, including Ehattesaht students and youth, in the operation of the Zeballos River salmon hatchery including (but not limited to) brood-stock collection, fish husbandry and fry release. 5.Staff and youth will participate in all required protocol training and up to ten days of micro-trolling sampling for juvenile Chinook salmon during October-March period.
fields.dfo_report: 1.Results of escapement surveys according to survey schedules as follows:a.Salmon Escapement Enumeration Survey results including dates of snorkel survey results will be put on Stream Inspection Logs and bio-samples are provided to DFO Stock Assessment (cc DFO WCVI AFS Manager) in-season. The actual dates and method of reporting to DFO will be included in the Third Quarter and AFS Year End Report. 2.Summary of monitoring concerns and resulting referrals will be included in the AFS Year End Report including which agency and contact the concerns were delivered to.3.Summary of the status of the Zeballos River salmon access improvements feasibility, and resulting referrals will be included in the AFS Year End Report including to which agency and contact person the concerns were delivered.4. Summary of number of youth and volunteers assisting with each of the Tahtahtis (Zeballos) River hatchery activities they were involved with, to be included in the AFS Year End Report. Description of hatchery activities by Ehattesaht Fisheries program staff will also be included in AFS Year End Report.5. Summary of AFS funded Ehattesaht Fisheries staff activities and Ehattesaht youth's participation in micro-trolling activities will be reported in the AFS Year End Report as well as all required reporting/deliverables to DFO Science.

fields.task_description: 1.Hesquiaht Fisheries staff conduct salmon escapement surveys. 2.Hesquiaht Fisheries staff will construct new or re-establish old trails alongside some of the streams that will undergo salmon escapement surveys.   3.Hesquiaht Fisheries staff will conduct general monitoring and biological surveys of Hesquiaht Ha-houlthee. 4.Hesquiaht Fisheries will continue to work with Central Westcoast Forest Society (CWFS) on stream restoration work for Ay-yi-sagh Creek, the extent of work completed will be dependent on external funding.  AFS funding pays for Hesquiaht Fisheries staff wages and related expenses, if funding is not available through CWFS.  CWFS pays for any other expenditures required for the project.  Hesquiaht Fisheries only participates in the work if funding is available by CWFS.5. Hesquiaht Fisheries staff will support the construction and installation of a counting fence at Purdon Creek and Hisnit Lake to enumerate adult salmon escapement.

fields.activity_title: Stock Assessment and Fisheries Management- Hesquiaht
fields.expected_results: 1.Conduct escapement surveys for coho and chum on Ah'ta'apq, Tsa-ya, Sachie, Ay-yi-sagh, Yaaksis, Maahpe, Purdon, Tsa-Aio and Teamut streams according to a survey schedule developed with the NTC biologist, DFO South Coast Stock Assessment staff and Hesquiaht Fisheries.2.Construct or re-establish and maintain one or more trails alongside a stream scheduled to undergo salmon escapements surveys.3. Conduct one or more assessments such as herring spawn, sea otter, crab, geoduck or clam surveys in Hesquiaht Ha-houlthee.4.Conduct one or more stream restoration projects in Hesquiaht Ha-houlthee, dependant on external funding.5.Support from the Hesquiaht Fisheries staff to construct and install as well as operate fish fences on Purdon Creek and Hisnit Lake for the collection of salmon escapement data.  Data provided to DFO South Coast Stock Assessment and DFO AFS Manager at the end of the project.
fields.dfo_report: 1.Results of salmon escapement surveys using Stream Inspection Logs provided to DFO Stock Assessment (cc DFO WCVI AFS Manager) in-season. The actual dates and method of reporting to DFO will be included in the AFS Year End Report.2.Summary of results maintaining trail access in support of salmon escapement surveys will be included in the AFS Year End Report (at least two photos will be included). 3.Summary of survey and monitoring (i.e. fish fence counts) results provided to relevant DFO staff (cc DFO WCVI AFS Manager) and dates and results of survey listed in AFS Year End Report. 4.AFS Year End Report will include a brief update on stream restoration projects.5.Salmon Escapement Enumeration Survey results will be provided in the AFS Year End Report.

fields.task_description: 1.Mowachaht/Muchalaht Fisheries staff conducts escapement surveys according to survey schedule developed with Uu-a-thluk Regional Biologist and DFO South Coast Stock Assessment staff. a.Enumerate Oktwanch River (Gold River) sockeye and Chinook at Burman River, visual surveys (2-3 surveys) from September to November. b.Mowachaht/Muchalaht Fisheries staff will implement a bus route CREEL monitoring program for Gold River sockeye fisheries to estimate catch and effort by seine, dipnet and hook and line.2.With the assistance of external funding from the Canada Food Inspection Agency (CFIA), Mowachaht/Muchalaht Fisheries staff conduct bio-toxin monitoring from May to October. 3. Mowachaht/Muchalaht Fisheries staff conduct general monitoring of Mowachaht/Muchalaht Ha-houlthee and report issues or concerns to the community and relevant agencies.4. Mowachaht/Muchalaht Fisheries staff works closely with the Nootka Sound Watershed Society (NSWS) and Conuma hatchery staff (e.g., salmon collections, juvenile salmon releases and feeding net pen chinook and chum).5.Mowachaht/Muchalaht Fisheries staff work with DFO and the Organization's staff on the planning and development of an Excess Salmon to Spawning Requirements (ESSR) agreement for Conuma River chinook, coho and chum if abundances are deemed sufficient.6.Mowachaht/Muchalaht Fisheries staff works with DFO to coordinate for fall salmon stock assessment survey planning and information flow.

fields.activity_title: Stock Assessment and Fisheries Management- Mowachaht/Muchalaht
fields.expected_results: 1.Salmon escapement survey work by the Mowachaht/Muchalaht Fisheries staff includes:a.Conducting escapement surveys for sockeye salmon on the Oktwanch River (Gold) from September to early November.b.Conducting a bus route survey for Oktwanch River (Gold River) sockeye fisheries c. Supporting contracted escapement projects with DFO StAD tentatively identified at Tsowwin, Canton, and Oktwanch and Burman Rivers. d.Supporting Conuma Chinook mark-recapture2.Marine bio-toxins are monitored weekly from May to October for CFIA.3.Monitor the environment in the Mowachaht/ Muchalaht Ha-houlthee and report concerns to community and appropriate agency staff such Environment & Climate Change Canada, DFO, Province of BC Forest, Lands and Natural Resource Operations and Rural Development, etc. (e.g., derelict float homes, logging erosion, rate of cut considerations affecting salmon production).4. Assist Nootka Sound Watershed Society (NSWS) with activities in relation to production Chinook from the Gold and Burman Rivers satellite programs with Conuma hatchery (e.g., Chinook, chum and brood-stock collections, biosampling provide NSWS assistance for feeding net pen Chinook, assist Conuma hatchery staff in release of juvenile salmon) and participate in the annual production planning for Conuma hatchery with DFO SEP staff 5.Development of an ESSR Agreement for Conuma Chinook, Coho and Chum. Mowachaht/Muchalaht Fisheries program staff and the Organization's Northern Region Fisheries Biologist will work with Conuma DFO enhancement Facility Manager and DFO WCVI AFS Manager in August.6.Participate in juvenile fall salmon stock assessment survey planning with DFO Stock Assessment Biologist.
fields.dfo_report: 1.Results of escapement surveys according to survey schedules as follows:a.Oktwanch and Burman rivers Salmon Escapement Enumeration Survey results will be reported to DFO South Coast Stock Assessment Biologist (cc DFO WCVI AFS Manager) on Stream Inspection Logs in-season.  The actual dates and method of reporting to DFO will be included in the AFS Year End Report.b.Reports summarizing CREEL results including effort, catch and gear type, provided to DFO South Coast Stock Assessment (cc DFO WCVI AFS Manager) in-season. The actual dates and method of reporting to DFO will be included in the AFS Year End Report.2.Samples are sent to CFIA weekly from May to October via pre-paid courier. Provide date and method of submission to CFIA in the AFS Year End Report.3.Summary of monitoring concerns and resulting referrals will be included in the AFS Year End Report including which agency and contact the concerns were delivered to.4.Summary of number of employees assisting Conuma hatchery and list of activities they were involved with, to be included in the AFS Year End Report.5.Summary of Mowachaht/Muchalaht priorities and  recommendations regarding Conuma hatchery production planning and other salmon enhancement efforts for Area 25 will be provided to DFO SEP through production planning process.6.Signed ESSR Agreement (if viable ESSR opportunity develops) and completion of all catch reporting requirements  provided to DFO Resource Manager (Amy Greenwood) weekly. Provide date and method of submission to DFO in the AFS Year End Report.7.Salmon Escapement Enumeration Survey planning results and decisions will be provided in the AFS Year End Report.

fields.activity_title: Stock Assessment and Fisheries Management- Tla-o-qui-aht
fields.expected_results: 1.Conduct broodstock capture in the Upper Kennedy River. Training of hatchery staff, dealing with the fertilization, incubation and rearing of chinook eggs and fry.2.Plan to expand Tla-o-qui-aht's hatchery operations by investigating the feasibility of other enhancement sites and enhancement of other species (i.e. Sockeye). This will be done in conjunction with Kennedy Watershed Sockeye restoration planning.3.Conduct and/or assist with escapement surveys according to survey schedule developed with DFO and Tla-o-qui-aht Fisheries staff on Kennedy River systems (i.e. Muriel Lake, Staghorn Creek, Angora Creek and Lower Kennedy and Kennedy Lake).4.Conduct three or more general monitoring surveys (e.g. sea otters) and other surveys as contracted by DFO (if applicable). Monitor the environment in Tla-o-qui-aht Ha-houlthee and report concerns to community and appropriate agency staff such as Ministry of Environment and DFO.  When a specific DFO survey contract is awarded, the report on surveys will distinguish AFS funded activities versus non-AFS funded activities.
fields.dfo_report: 1.Summary of broodstock capture dates and activities supporting SEP activities in the Kennedy watershed will be included in the AFS Year End Report2. The progress on Tla-o-qui-aht's hatchery operations will be summarized in AFS Year End Report. 3.Salmon Escapement Enumeration Survey results will be reported to DFO Stock Assessment (cc DFO WCVI AFS Manager) and DFO Community Advisor on SILs, in-season, according to survey schedule developed with DFO and Tla-o-qui-aht via pre-paid priority post envelopes provided by DFO. The actual dates and method of reporting to DFO will be included in the AFS Year End Report.4.Summary of results will be included in the AFS Year End Report. 5.Summary of survey and monitoring results to relevant DFO staff (cc WCVI AFS Manager), and dates and results of survey listed in AFS Year End Report. (e.g., sea otter survey information will be reported to DFO Science Branch, in-season and summarized in the AFS Year End Report).

The actual dates and method of reporting to DFO will be included in the AFS Year End Report.4.Summary of results will be included in the AFS Year End Report. 5.Summary of survey and monitoring results to relevant DFO staff (cc WCVI AFS Manager), and dates and results of survey listed in AFS Year End Report. (e.g., sea otter survey information will be reported to DFO Science Branch, in-season and summarized in the AFS Year End Report).

fields.task_description: 1.Ditidaht Fisheries Supervisor and other fisheries staff annually work on food and ceremonial Fishing Plan(s) which are provided to DFO through the Uu-a-thluk/ DFO Joint Technical Working Group meetings.2.Ditidaht Fisheries staff provides catch monitoring information to DFO throughout the year.
fields.element_title: Food, Social and Ceremonial (FSC) Fisheries Management
fields.activity_title: Food and Ceremonial Fisheries Management- Ditidaht
fields.expected_results: 1.Conduct broodstock capture in the Upper Kennedy River. Training of hatchery staff, dealing with the fertilization, incubation and rearing of chinook eggs and fry.2.Plan to expand Tla-o-qui-aht's hatchery operations by investigating the feasibility of other enhancement sites and enhancement of other species (i.e. Sockeye). This will be done in conjunction with Kennedy Watershed Sockeye restoration planning.3.Conduct and/or assist with escapement surveys according to survey schedule developed with DFO and Tla-o-qui-aht Fisheries staff on Kennedy River systems (i.e. Muriel Lake, Staghorn Creek, Angora Creek and Lower Kennedy and Kennedy Lake).4.Conduct three or more general monitoring surveys (e.g. sea otters) and other surveys as contracted by DFO (if applicable). Monitor the environment in Tla-o-qui-aht Ha-houlthee and report concerns to community and appropriate agency staff such as Ministry of Environment and DFO.  When a specific DFO survey contract is awarded, the report on surveys will distinguish AFS funded activities versus non-AFS funded activities.

fields.task_description: 1. The Organization will install and operate adult/carcass enumeration fences at three remote locations in the Taku River Drainage for the purposes of enumerating adult salmon returns, ensuring passage and assessing the biological stock characteristics.
fields.activity_title: Stock Assessment
fields.expected_results: 1. Employment of up to 8 Members for approximately 10 person months; develop technical capacity in stock assessment techniques. 2.Cumulative counts, tag recovery/loss information and number of samples obtained to date will be reported to the Fisheries Coordinator on a weekly basis, on Wednesday of each week, and this information will in turn be provided to DFO Senior Stock Assessment Biologist, Aaron Foos.
fields.dfo_report: 1. The PM will provide samples and associated data to DFO Senior Stock Assessment Biologist, Aaron Foos, by September 30. 2. Summary reports on the individual tasks are included in the Year End Report.
