fields.task_description: Conduct work to expand and deepen the rock notch at in the Silver Salmon River (site SR3) to increase flow to the river and left side of the obstacle, impacting on salmon migration in the river to Kuthai Lake.
fields.activity_title: Silver Salmon River Fish Passage Improvements
fields.expected_results: The TRT staff to complete assessment of work site obstruction impacting on migration of salmon up the Silver Salmon River.  Set up safety rope systems and minor instream diversions to ensure a dry work area (where required) and exclude any fish. Rock work will be conducted by a combination of hammer drill and rock saw to deepen the river left notch/kerf cuts inside the existing rock work area, to bring a more even split of flow between the river right side of the obstruction and the river left side. This is intended to provide better depth and improved low flow passage through the passage enhancement works. Once completed assessment of site will include jump attempt monitoring and digital video recording of jump attempts, as well as beaver dam management within the river.
fields.dfo_report: All of the field activities will be captured in a summary report. Products/Reports to provide to DFO.

fields.activity_title: Training

fields.task_description: (Existing activity under AFS) Lengthening the duration of and providing additional support for the mark-recpature program (FYI, funding received from other sources as well: Province's Environmental Stewardship Initiative and for steelhead tagging). Sockeye and coho selected for tagging will be tagged with TBA-1, Hallprint tags and collect biological samples including scale in Upper Bulkley River, Morice Lake, and Atna Lake.
fields.activity_title: Stock Assessment/Mark Recapture
fields.expected_results: 1.Maintain boats and vehicle for the tagging program. 2. Installation of bridges to Fishing sites, safety ropes, maintenance of project related Fishing gear. 3.Conduct pre-season test Fishing to determine when sampling activity should begin. 4. Hire labourers to transport equipment and gear for tagging operations, and to maintain and repair truck, insure truck, inspect truck for compliance with Department of Highways regulations. 5. Update the daily tagging data form developed in 2014 as necessary. This form is used to make in season estimates. 6.The FM will help ensure data is gathered and stored in a manner that safeguards the data, and ensures the data is accurate. 7.Conduct aerial spawner counts for Chinook, Coho, Sockeye and Pink in conjunction with DFO. 8.Conduct dead pitches in the Nanika River to supplement the Mark/Recapture program and swim Nanika River to count Sockeye spawners, noting tagged to untagged rations.  DFO will generate population estimates. 9. Conduct stream walks in the Morice River 1km from Morice Lake at the Dunes for Chinook enumeration. 10.Conduct stream walks in the Morice River Mainstem to count Sockeye and Sockeye spawners.11.Provide DFO Stock Assessment and Skeena Fisheries Commission Staff with Coho estimate data. This will be used in conjunction with the Tyee Test DNA to produce a total Skeena Coho population estimate. 12.Maintain employment for existing technical staff for the extended duration of the program. 13.Continued expansion of technical capacity for the Wet'suwet'en Treaty Office Society Fisheries Program.
fields.dfo_report: 1.Submit spawner count survey reports to DFO Stock Assessment for the Nanika and Gosnell Rivers. 2.Submit enumeration figures to DFO Stock Assessment for the Morice and Atna Lakes.3.Submit enumeration figures to DFO Stock Assessment for Chinook and Sockeye in the Morice River. 4.Submit Sockeye DNA samples to DFO Pacific Biological Station in Nanaimo. 5.Submit scale samples to Ryan Whitmore, DFO Stock Biologist, in Smithers. 6.Enter into Access database the Moricetown Canyon Tagging and Beach Seine Tagging data and submit to Smithers DFO Stock Assessment. 7.Submit in the Year End Report a summary of Stock Assessment activities and results

fields.task_description: Wet'suwet'en Fisheries Staff will conduct habitat protection and monitoring activities to assist in habitat baseline information collection, habitat protection and conservation efforts within the Wet'suwet'en asserted area. 2. The Organization will monitor the functionality of various in-stream structures including culverts and forest service roads within the Morice Watershed. The Organization will review proposals and attend any meetings related to proposed linear development or resource extraction development within the Wet'suwet'en asserted area.
fields.activity_title: Habitat Monitoring and Restoration
fields.expected_results: 1.Water quality, flow and temperature monitoring in Moricetown Canyon. 2.Continue the existing water quality monitoring program for the special water management area in the upper Morice watershed that was created through the Morice LRMP. 3.Review plans and attend meetings for any mines, pipelines or other industrial developments that may have an impact on habitat within the Wet'suwet'en asserted area. 4.Country food (food Fish) will be monitored for contaminants. 5.Habitat and Fish inventory at pipeline crossing sites. 6.Establish baseline data for country foods (food Fish) down streams of potential crossing locations.
fields.dfo_report: 1.Information collected and concerns from the Wet'suwet'en Fisheries Staff specific to a land or water development proposal will be provided to the Office of the Wet'suwet'en, DFO, and Provincial Governments and to various industry representatives as applicable. 2.A summary of Habitat Monitoring and Restoration activities will be provided to DFO in the Year End Report. 3. Any habitat violation concerns will be reported immediately to Smithers DFO C&P Officers.

fields.task_description: The Organization will purchase a pickup truck to replace the aging vehicle that is in need of extensive repairs.
fields.activity_title: Pickup Truck Purchase

fields.task_description: Catch Monitoring of all species will continue in Moricetown Canyon.  Data will be used to calculate inseason catch estimates of the Wet'suwet'en Fisheries and be reported weekly to DFO in Prince Rupert and Smithers.
fields.element_title: Food, Social and Ceremonial (FSC) Fisheries Management
fields.activity_title: Catch Monitoring and Reporting
fields.expected_results: 1.Up to 8 seasonal catch monitor positions will be created. 2.Species and catch numbers released and observed will be recorded at 2 hour intervals from dawn to dusk at FSC Fishing sites. 3.Monitoring data will be entered into a Microsoft Access database.
fields.dfo_report: 1.In-season FSC catch numbers will be submitted to DFO Implementation Officer, Andrea Komlos, on a weekly basis. 2.A summary of FSC harvest will be provided by October 31 of that year and within the Year End Report and submitted to DFO in Smithers.

fields.task_description: Replace existing motor.
fields.activity_title: Purchase Mercury 200 Optimax Powerhead Boat Motor and jet pump package

fields.task_description: Build a tagging boat suitable for Bulkley River and AFG activities.
fields.activity_title: Operational Capacity Funding- Capital Acquisition; Boat hull replacement

fields.task_description: Wet'suwet'en Fisheries Staff will continue with the Mark/Recapture Project that provides a population estimate of salmon destined for spawning grounds above the Moricetown Canyon in season, as well as to tag Steelhead for other studies that may occur during the fall and spring.  In addition to tagging the salmonids, data such as sex, length and condition is compiled.  Special emphasis will be given to observe/record the damage conditions of salmon this year with consequent monitoring on the spawning beds. Research suggests that high infection rates with a fungus (Saprolegnia spp.) entering the fish body through net marks and other skin damage causes significant mortalities.   The Mark/Recapture program is mainly funded through stock assessment and the top up of funds is supported through the AFS program.

fields.task_description: 1.The FC/FT will coordinate catch monitoring and reporting as agreed to in the AFS Agreement. 2.The FC/FT, in consultation with DFO, will develop a detailed operational plan that outlines the proposed fishing activities for the year and the specific fisheries management activities to be undertaken by the Organization.3.The FC/FT will collect all known weekly catch information for all fish including shellfish harvested by the Organization or designate, in a suitable format to the DFO Area Species Coordinators as identified by Jonathan Joe, DFO Resource Manager.4.The FC will employ individual(s) as it deems necessary to undertake catch monitoring and reportings. 5.The FC/FT will maintain records of catch throughout the year for all species possible and summarize information for a final report.6.The FC/FT will assign and manage fishing permits, including communal licences to designated persons and vessels.
fields.element_title: Food, Social and Ceremonial (FSC) Fisheries Management
fields.activity_title: FSC Fisheries Management
fields.expected_results: 1.All data collected by the Aboriginal Monitors will be submitted monthly to DFO NC Aboriginal programs staff and also provided on the weekly in-season calls. 2.Any incidents will be documented and reported to the Kitsumkalum Aboriginal Fishery Guardian.  The Aboriginal Fishery Guardian will fill in the proper required documentation and submit it to the DFO C&P staff in Terrace.
fields.dfo_report: 1.A summary Catch Monitoring Report will be submitted with the Year End Report.

fields.task_description: The Organization will sample Chinook and Sockeye salmon harvested in the Upper Stikine River FSC fishery, implement adult Chinook salmon assessment projects, and conduct aerial surveys for Stikine River sockeye and Coho salmon
fields.activity_title: Stock Assessment
fields.expected_results: 1.Employment of 4 community members for approximately 9 months; develop technical capacity in stock assessment techniques. 2. Achieve target samples, apportioned to run strength and according to protocols included in operational plans. 3.Cumulative counts, tag recovery information, and number of samples obtained to date from the Upper Stikine are reported to the Fisheries Manager on a weekly basis. 4. Index areas for Sockeye and Coho salmon are surveyed by helicopter. 5.Assessment of the Chinook salmon run to the Little Tahltan River using video enumeration methodologies.
fields.dfo_report: 1.The Fisheries Manager shall provide Upper Stikine River samples by mail and associated data in excel via email to DFO Stock Assessment Project Coordinator Johnny.Sembsmoen@dfo-mpo.gc.ca by September 1, 2021. 2.Tallies of aerial counts by index areas (shared survey with DFO - results are tallied and included in Transboundary Technical Committee annual reports). 3.Copies of the daily Little Tahltan River Chinook salmon count files to Stock Assessment Project Coordinator Johnny.Sembsmoen@dfo-mpo.gc.ca by September 1, 2021 for verification and inclusion in the Transboundary Technical Committee annual reports. 4.Summary Reports on the individual projects are included in the Year End Report.

fields.name: Conservation and Enhancement of Pacific Salmonids in the Nanaimo Watershed
fields.project_description: Pursue enhancement goals and objectives for each brood year outlined in the approved Integrated Fisheries Management Plan Production Plan for the Nanaimo and Chemainus River watersheds. To support stock rebuilding, raise and release up to: �  225,000 summer run and 425,000 fall run Nanaimo chinook ;  67,500 Chemainus chinook salmon ; 200,000 Nanaimo coho ; To support harvest access, raise and release up to:  900,000 Nanaimo chum ; 1,000,000 pink salmon
fields.other_funding_sources: Nanaimo River Stewardship Society,Community Donations,Volunteer labour,VIU Practicum

fields.name: Conservation and Enhancement of Pacific Salmonids in the Nanaimo Watershed
fields.project_description: To fulfill the purpose of promoting conservation and enchancement in the Nanaimo River area, the NRSS undertakes and supports public education and outreach activities. The activities range from volunteer participation in salmon enhancement activities and educational viewing opportunities, to school programs and salmon fry release opportunities for the public and students. Most stewardship activities align with the timing of salmon enhancement activities across the year.
fields.other_funding_sources: Nanaimo River Stewardship Society,Community Donations,Volunteer labour,VIU Practicum

fields.name: Thornton Creek Hatchery: Conservation and Enhancement of Pacific Salmonids in Barkley Sound
fields.project_description: TCH supports conservation and rebuilding, and harvest enhancement objectives in the Ucluelet area watersheds, Toquaht watershed and enhancement activities in the Clayoquot Sound watersheds that include Tranquil and Upper Kennedy River watersheds. Year round tasks involve implementing best management practices of salmon culture techniques including Salmonid broodstock capture, holding, handling, sorting, spawning, incubation - (inventory, fungus treatments - salt, parasite S, shocking, picking (hand, machine), ponding, marking, flows, experiments, marking (otolith, clips, tags, other), rearing in raceways, channels, tubs, netpens/seapens (diet/growth, pond maintenance, water quality, flow), fish health management, treatment, biosecurity (internal, external), transport, release, adult and juvenile enumeration and sampling. Program preparation, monitoring, troubleshooting, maintenance and clean-up are ongoing tasks. Program strategic planning and broader facilities maintenance occur during periods of reduced biological activity.

fields.name: Thornton Creek Hatchery: Conservation and Enhancement of Pacific Salmonids in Barkley Sound
fields.project_description: Thornton Creek Hatchery works collaboratively with First Nations, volunteer community groups, municipal and federal governments, industry, educational institutions, and other stakeholder groups. The hatchery supports Community Involvement Program Stream to Sea Education programming, including Salmonids in the Classroom. Most stewardship activities align with the timing of salmon enhancement activities throughout the year.

fields.project_description: Improve the delivery and accuracy of the chum enumeration program, escapement estimate, and stream surveys for Fiscal Year 2020-2021 by providing additional staffing, equipment, and general operating expenses.

fields.name: Operational Capacity Funding - 4x4 Pickup Truck Purchase
fields.project_description: The organization will purchase a 4x4 � ton pickup truck to replace its primary fisheries vehicle which is from 2005, and is worn out from 15 years of heavy use.

fields.name: Somass Watershed Sockeye Salmon Enumeration
fields.project_description: This project focuses on the Somass River watershed. The Somass is one of the largest sockeye rivers in B.C.  It is a crucial component of the Organization's food, social and ceremonial catch as well as the other five First Nations in the Barkley Sound Watershed.  The enumeration work has been conducted by the Organization and DFO over the past 18 years. This activity seeks to continue and build on that work.  The work focuses on the technical aspect of collaborative management, and involves the collection, sampling and dissemination of the Sockeye enumeration data. A biologist has been hired to work with the Organization's Members to help achieve this goal. The short term result of this work will be increased capacity regarding technical science methodology. The Organization sees this as a continuing step to achieving the longer term goal of enabling members to understand, analyze, and apply data to support their interests in collaborative resource management regarding the watershed and approach areas. The goal of this project is to increase the capacity of the Organization to engage in an expanded collaborative relationship with DFO and ensure sustainable management of fish in the Organization's asserted traditional area.

fields.name: Fall Salmon (non-Sockeye) Stock Assessment
fields.project_description: The Organization works with DFO to conduct adult salmon enumeration and biological sampling at the Stamp, Sproat River and Great Central Lake fish ways from May until November. Work is done under contract with DFO South Coast Stock Assessment Unit (Diana Dobson). The Organization's AFS funded guardian (non-designated) and fisheries manager assist other Hupacasath staff with this work as well as interact with DFO assessment staff regularly throughout the duration of the program. 2.

fields.name: Food, Social and Ceremonial Fisheries Management - Hupacasath First Nation
fields.project_description: The Organization�s Fisheries staff engages their community members to develop their fishing plans. Hupacasath's FSC Somass salmon fishing plans are part of their overall Tsu-ma-uss Fisheries Agreement with DFO and their non-salmon FSC fishing plans are part of this Agreement. Hupacasath Fisheries regularly engages and communicates Hupacasath FSC fishing plans and opportunities to its Members. The Organization�s Fisheries staff provide catch monitoring information to DFO throughout the year according to agreed upon Schedules.

fields.name: Surplus funding - Juvenile Sockeye Stock Assessment Acoustic Trawl Surveys
fields.project_description: Hupacasath Fisheries has been conducting ATS surveys for the past three seasons. These surveys are an essential tool in assessing the productivity of sockeye nursery lakes and provide data that is directly used in forecasting the adult returns. Locally Hupacasath FN has been conducting two surveys at each Great Central Lake and Sproat Lake annually, but with the recent declines in the stocks in both systems the importance of monitoring these populations has grown. We are proposing two additional surveys at each lake be conducted to ensure accurate pre-smolt estimates can be generated and any mortality events in the lakes be identified. The cost for these additional surveys is outlined below. To date the Hupacasath Fisheries department has not completed any surveys in Henderson Lake due to access issues, but with the recent development of a smaller, more mobile set up, there is an opportunity to restart these surveys. One survey will be funded within this agreement. This survey will provide very important data for DFO stock assessment to accurately forecast the sockeye returns to Henderson Lake. The cost to conduct this survey is detailed below.

fields.name: Surplust funding - Fisheries Program Truck (Capital Acquisition)
Spring and Early Summer Salmon Enumeration at Sproat River Fishway and Stamp Falls Fishway
fields.project_description: To estimate escapement of salmon using video counts from the Sproat and Stamp Falls fishways. Counting operations will run from mid-May through mid-Aug, and a sub-sample of videos from both sites will be reviewed to identify fish to species and estimate the portion of marked fish. Biological samples will also be collected (2-3 times per week from fish at both sites to estimate the age and sex composition of escapement).

fields.name: Rotary Screw Trap (PST)
fields.project_description: To hire a company to begin construction of a rotary screw trap (RST). Components to construct are a floating fish rotating screen including a steel trailer; aluminum pontoon base, aluminum fish catch box, and an aluminum cones catching drum. The full estimated cost to build the RST is $51,450.00 plus taxes. The $9,345.00 will be spent this fiscal and the remaining balance will be covered in the 2021-2022 fiscal year. The RST will be used for existing projects to estimate the abundance of the Smolt Out-Migration through Robertson Creek and Sproat River.

fields.name: FSC Salmon Catch Monitoring of all Metlakatla and designated non-members fishing (under Metlakatla designation) in the approach waters to the Skeena River (not including sub-areas 4-12 and 4-15)
fields.project_description: MAR will conduct routine catch monitoring to encourage compliance with the conditions of communal licences.  The MAR staff will conduct on-grounds inspection of personal and vessel designations, observe catch methods, and monitor harvest levels.  MAR operates a FSC salmon validation and distribution program from June - September to assist with FSC needs.  Through this program, salmon are distributed to band members, and dockside validators record by-catch and salmon catch numbers from each vessel that delivers to the program.  Landing stations will be located in Metlakatla and at Metlakatla's Fisheries dock in Prince Rupert.  Records of validation; such as dates, vessels, number of salmon, and distribution to membership will be maintained.

fields.name: Stock Assessment
fields.project_description: 1.Coldwater River Coho: NWSFA will undertake an adult Coho enumeration project at the Coldwater River fence.  The project will involve enumeration by sex, as well as adipose clip and CWT status through the utilization of a trap box and Sonar technology.  CWT status will be assessed by the removal of marked fish for sampling. Fish released upstream of the trap box will be externally marked to determine if fish have been previously handled. This will assist in the calculation of clip rates from upstream sampling efforts as clip rates will change with the removal of clipped fish at the fence.  Specific technical detail of this project can be found in Supplemental Conditions/Provisions for Fiscal Year 2020-2021. 2.Nicola River and tributaries Coho: As time, budget, and weather conditions allow, other known Coho spawning areas will be checked, and counts of adult Coho performed 3 times over the 3 weeks of expected peak spawn:  Nicola River near Dot ranch; upstream of Nicola and Coldwater confluence to Nicola lake dam and upper Nicola River; plus tributaries such as Guichon Creek, Clapperton Creek, Spahomin Creek, Quilchena Creek and Chutter Ranch side channel. 3.Nicola River Chinook:  NWSFA staff will carry out the carcass recovery and sampling work associated with mark/recapture activities.  Carcass recovery activities will be undertaken in the Nicola River mainstem between the outlet of Nicola Lake and the Dot Trestle, lower Clapperton Creek, Coldwater River downstream of the IR#1 bridge, and Spius Creek downstream of Little Box Canyon. If appropriate (budget- and fish-presence dependant), the upper Nicola River between Nicola Lake and Douglas Lake, and Spahomin Creek, will also be inspected. Other possible Chinook refuge habitat will be surveyed as time, budget and weather conditions allow.

fields.name: FSC Catch Monitoring (Siska)
fields.project_description: Under contract with the STC, the Siska Band will carry out in-person interviews with fishers to collect Food, Social and Ceremonial (FSC) salmon catch information at Siska fishing sites. Crews will also collect biological samples as agreed to with DFO. Catch data is submitted to DFO weekly.  Meetings occur pre-season with DFO for the purpose of training and in-season to share information, resolve issues of concern and facilitate effective coordination of catch monitoring and fishing activities.Specific tasks will include:1.A catch monitoring schedule will be completed by the Siska Band in collaboration with the NWSFA Fisheries Technologist and DFO.  DFO will lead  orientation(s) for monitors prior to start of the program which may include a site visit to fishing areas.2.Monitors will carry out the field data collection according to schedule and will report missed shifts or changes to the schedule to the Fisheries Technologist (or a designated NWSFA alternate staff as agreed to with DFO). The Fisheries Technologist (or alternate) will update DFO as soon as possible to enable schedule modification. Any conservation and protection concerns that monitors have during their shift will be reported to the Fisheries Technologist (or alternate) who will contact the appropriate DFO staff as soon as possible.3.During the program, the NWSFA Fisheries Technologist will verify that the data sheets match the schedule and will coordinate with Siska and/or DFO to address data quality concerns in-season.

fields.name: Coldwater River Coho and Nicola River and Tributaries Coho
fields.project_description: Top up Key Element A/Activity 2: Stock Assessment Coldwater River Coho and Nicola River and Tributaries Coho. fields.project_description: Top up Key Element A/Activity 2: Stock Assessment Nicola River Chinook. Additional funds will allow for full implementation of the Nicola chinook carcass recovery program.

fields.name: Stock Assessment and Fisheries Management- Ahousaht
fields.project_description: 1.Ahousaht Fisheries staff conducts escapement surveys according to a survey schedule developed with Ahousaht Fisheries, the Organization�s Central Region Fisheries Biologist, the Ahousaht/ Fish Farm Enhancement Committee, and with DFO South Coast Stock Assessment staff. 2.With the assistance of external funding from Canadian Food Inspection agency (CFIA), Ahousaht Fisheries staff conducts bio-toxin monitoring.  AFS funding pays for Ahousaht Fisheries staff wages and related expenses to assist with the monitoring.  CFIA funding pays for Ahousaht Fisheries boat operating expenses and shipping of samples.3.Ahousaht Fisheries conduct general monitoring, and biological and enforcement surveys of Ahousaht Ha-houlthee and report issues or concerns to the community and relevant agencies.

fields.name: Stock Assessment and Fisheries Management-Ditidaht
fields.project_description: 1.Ditidaht Fisheries staff conducts escapement surveys according to survey schedule developed with DFO South Coast Stock Assessment and Ditidaht. a.Enumerate adult Hobiton River sockeye by installing and operating an adult salmon counting fence from April to June. b.Prepare the juvenile trap site and install Rotary Screw Trap (provided by DFO) with assistance from DFO South Coast Stock Assessment and Uu-a-thluk staff. c.Two to three Cheewaht salmon spawner surveys will occur from October to November. d.Nitinat Lake assessment fisheries:  using food and ceremonial fisheries and Nitinat hatchery chinook, chum and coho broodstock collections to gather information with DFO on run-timing, distribution and age structure of chinook, coho and chum returning to Nitinat Lake from August to November. AFS covers the wages of the Fisheries Manager and some boat and other equipment expenses.  Ditidaht uses internal funding to cover all other costs. 2.Nitinat Lake crab are monitored and assessed at least six times throughout the year.3.Ditidaht staff will work with the Organization's staff to develop and implement groundfish monitoring and assessment in DFO Statistical Areas 21/121.4.With the assistance of external funding from the Canada Food Inspection agency (CFIA), Ditidaht Fisheries staff conducts bio-toxin monitoring from May to October. AFS funding pays for Ditidaht Fisheries staff wages and related expenses to assist with the monitoring. fields.name: Stock Assessment and Fisheries Management- Ehattesaht

fields.name: Moricetown M&R
fields.project_description: Wet'suwet'en Fisheries Staff will continue with the Mark/Recapture Project that provides a population estimate of salmon destined for spawning grounds above the Moricetown Canyon in season, as well as to tag Steelhead for other studies that may occur during the fall and spring.  In addition to tagging the salmonids, data such as sex, length and condition is compiled.  Special emphasis will be given to observe/record the damage conditions of salmon this year with consequent monitoring on the spawning beds. Research suggests that high infection rates with a fungus (Saprolegnia spp.) entering the fish body through net marks and other skin damage causes significant mortalities.   The Mark/Recapture program is mainly funded through stock assessment and the top up of funds is supported through the AFS program.

fields.project_description: 1.The Organization will work collaboratively with BC Parks and DFO on the stewardship of the Goldstream Watershed by maintaining regular communications and attending related planning meetings. 2.The Organization's staff will pursue opportunities to be trained in stock assessment techniques, which may include but is not limited to, joining stream walks and/or arranging meetings with DFO StAD to discuss stock assessment techniques).

fields.name: FSC Fisheries Management
fields.project_description: 1.The FC/FT will coordinate catch monitoring and reporting as agreed to in the AFS Agreement. 2.The FC/FT, in consultation with DFO, will develop a detailed operational plan that outlines the proposed fishing activities for the year and the specific fisheries management activities to be undertaken by the Organization.3.The FC/FT will collect all known weekly catch information for all fish including shellfish harvested by the Organization or designate, in a suitable format to the DFO Area Species Coordinators as identified by Jonathan Joe, DFO Resource Manager.4.The FC will employ individual(s) as it deems necessary to undertake catch monitoring and reportings. 5.The FC/FT will maintain records of catch throughout the year for all species possible and summarize information for a final report.6.The FC/FT will assign and manage fishing permits, including communal licences to designated persons and vessels.

fields.name: Stock Assessment
fields.project_description: Sample Chinook and sockeye salmon harvested in the upper Stikine River FSC fishery, implement adult Chinook salmon assessment projects, and conduct aerial surveys for Stikine River sockeye and coho salmon.

fields.name: Catch Monitoring and Reporting
fields.project_description: Fisheries Technician Officer (FTO) will issue fishing permits, collect food fish data, conduct creel survey, and monitor the food fishery based at Tahltan and will ensure that fish leaving the Telegraph Creek area are accompanied by valid Tahltan Fisheries transportation permits and will work with DFO/RCMP enforcement personnel where required. FTO will conduct a creel survey to determine catch and effort data for Chinook, and conduct monitoring to determine success of upstream migration of Chinook/Sockeye at and above a rock slide that may inhibit passage.

fields.name: Okanagan Chinook Recovery Program Implementation
fields.project_description: Okanagan Chinook Recovery Program Implementation of a developed recovery plan for spring and summer Chinook into the Okanagan basin (includes pilot studies to inform recovery plan). Wilsey Dam Fish Passage Provision of recommendations and support projects to ensure progress of improvements to fish passage through Wilsey Dam.

fields.name: Data assistance for Black Creek Counting fence & staffing support
fields.project_description: F/T  and P/T Fisheries Biologists. Data analysis assistance on projects such as Black Creek Counting Fence, surveys (crab, clam beach and prawn), plankton testing and stream enumeration.
fields.stock_management_unit: STRAIT OF GEORGIA COHO SALMON,GEORGIA STRAIT CHINOOK SALMON,INNER SOUTH COAST CHUM SALMON

fields.name: Biological and Technical Support (Staff and Contract Biologists)
fields.project_description: Biological and Technical Support (Staff and Contract Biologists) Provided to the LFFA and Lower Fraser First Nations to assist with fisheries resource management.
fields.stock_management_unit: FRASER PINK SALMON - ODD,FRASER SPRING RUN 52 CHINOOK SALMON

fields.name: Wet'snuwet'en Morice/Nanika Sockeye Recovery Process
fields.project_description: Coordinate Process to support recovery of Morice/Nanika Sockeye. Provide venue and facilitation of meeting. Travel for participants. Provide technical feedback and expertise to plans developed to support recovery

fields.name: Review of Skeena and Nass Sockeye Salmon Escapement Goals
fields.project_description: Provide technical expertise to support the Skeena and Nass sockeye escapement goal analysis project and provide 2 technical representatives to participate in a working group tasked with reviewing datasets, identify information gaps, prioritize further work, and develop an analysis plan for future phases of the project.

fields.name: Skeena Escapement Goals Analysis � Technical Committee Participation
fields.project_description: Participate in a review of escapement goals for Skeena and Nass Sockeye salmon through a technical working group. The working group will conduct a comprehensive review of the data, metrics and methods that can be used to develop biological benchmarks and assess stock status for different Skeena and Nass Sockeye populations.

fields.name: Sakinaw Sockeye Recovery Program (5PD27)
fields.project_description: Sakinaw sockeye project fence monitoring and maintenance, biological sampling and species subsampling, PIT tag detection and video review. Data sheets and sampling supplies provided to crew members and crew to provide completed data sheets and biological samples back to DFO.

fields.name: WCVI Creel Surveys
fields.project_description: Review and verify 2019 recreational and First Nation catch data, catch estimates and biological samples submitted. On water interviews so there will also be boat costs.

fields.name: LGS Chinook Restoration (Nanaimo R.) - B
fields.project_description: Review and complete an eelgrass assessment done in the Nanaimo River estuary.

fields.name: All Species DNA
fields.project_description: Procure, Provide PIT tags and technical staff to apply the tags in juvenile salmonids at Heydon Bay Creek in Loughborough Inlet / Procure, test and install PIT array in Heydon Bay Creek.

fields.name: Moricetown Sx & Co Marking and enumeration
Contract to Tofino Enhancement Society to work with Ahousaht fisheries to survey key Ahousaht rivers Bedwell, Megin, Moyeha, and other smaller systems.
fields.project_description: Bedwell, Cypre, Megin, Moyeha surveys. 3 SA in place: F1054-190055 (Snorkel surveys of Area 24 streams. Cypre (4), Megin (8 lower), Tranquil (9) surveys), F1054-190056 (Snorkel surveys of Area 24 streams. 8 surveys of Bedwell System), & F1054-190056 (Snorkel surveys of Area 24 streams. 4 surveys of Moyeha River) total value: 45,425k. To date, data recieved for 5 surveys conducted on the Bedwell/Ursus; 3 surveys on Cypre; 3 on Megin; 1 on the Moyeha; 1 on Warn Bay

fields.name: Heydon Fence
fields.project_description: To develop Heydon Creek as a sockeye, pink, chum and coho escapement indicator for the Area 13 Mainland Inlets area - covers portions of the fall program to collect: (1) fish counts by species to create species escapement estimates and (2) other biological info (e.g. lengths, scales, DNA, etc.).
fields.stock_management_unit: INNER SOUTH COAST CHUM SALMON,JOHNSTONE STRAIT/MAINLAND INLET COHO SALMON,ECVI/MAINLAND PINK SALMON

fields.name: Big Bar Landslide response: fish monitoring and tagging program
fields.project_description: Up to seven fisheries technicians, three to four from DFO Stock Assessment and two to three from Xwisten will collaboratively angle and tag Chinook salmon as they migrate through the Bridge River area in response to the Big Bar landslide. This element of the monitoring response is integral to determining passage at the Big Bar landslide. Covid-19 procedures have been designed and will be implemented to ensure work is completed in a safe manner.

fields.name: Fish patrol/catch monitoring program for FSC by the Bridge River Indian Band
fields.project_description: Monitors from the Organization will collect the Food, Social and Ceremonial (FSC) salmon catch information at Organization fishing sites during Sockeye and Chinook fishery openings, including fishing activity occurring on the Bridge River.  Monitors will help to educate Xwisten fishers on Xwisten traditional fishing laws by working with family fishing camps.  The Organization provides administrative support to the Xwisten Fish Patrol/Catch Monitoring Program and aids the Program with financial management, including the provision of office space, supplies, utilities, and IT support.

fields.name: Safety Training for FSC Catch Monitoring
fields.project_description: Catch Monitors will attend an Orientation session with DFO staff to review schedules and duties to be carried out.

fields.name: Extended Food, Social, and Ceremonial Fisheries Catch Monitoring
fields.project_description: One additional monitor from the Organization will be hired. This monitor will focus efforts on collecting Mark Rate information and sample adipose-clipped Chinook for coded wire tag (CWT) information in addition to conduct scale and DNA sampling for Sockeye.  This individual will also monitor fishing activity and interview fishers to collect catch and effort information by conducting in person interviews and effort counts.
